Age Aware Scheduling for Differentially-Private Federated Learning

Kuan-Yu Lin⋆, Hsuan-Yin Lin†, Yu-Pin Hsu‡, and Yu-Chih Huang⋆
⋆Institute of Communications Engineering, National Yang Ming Chiao Tung University
†Simula UiB, N–5006 Bergen, Norway
‡Department of Communication Engineering, National Taipei University
Abstract

This paper explores differentially-private federated learning (FL) across time-varying databases, delving into a nuanced three-way tradeoff involving age, accuracy, and differential privacy (DP). Emphasizing the potential advantages of scheduling, we propose an optimization problem aimed at meeting DP requirements while minimizing the loss difference between the aggregated model and the model obtained without DP constraints. To harness the benefits of scheduling, we introduce an age-dependent upper bound on the loss, leading to the development of an age-aware scheduling design. Simulation results underscore the superior performance of our proposed scheme compared to FL with classic DP, which does not consider scheduling as a design factor. This research contributes insights into the interplay of age, accuracy, and DP in federated learning, with practical implications for scheduling strategies.

I Introduction

Federated learning (FL) has emerged as a pivotal paradigm in machine learning, revolutionizing the way models are trained across decentralized data sources [1, 2, 3]. In an FL system, data are locally acquired and processed at each client, and then updated machine learning parameters are sent to a central server for aggregation. A major advantage of FL is that it enables local training without the exchange of personal data between the server and the clients. That offers a robust defense against potential eavesdropping by malicious actors. However, the risk of unintentional disclosure of private information remains, primarily through the analysis of variations in the parameters uploaded by clients. Thus, the application of differential privacy (DP) (or local DP) [4, 5, 6] in FL systems has received substantial attention (see, e.g., [7, 8, 9, 10]).

An often-overlooked aspect in most of the existing DP research is the impact of data freshness, especially concerning time-varying databases. To address this gap, recent research in [11] has introduced the concept of age-dependent DP. Their innovative approach recognizes the potential of aging (by the use of stale data inputs and/or the delay in releasing outputs) as a novel strategy for enhancing privacy. This method complements the conventional noise injection techniques typically employed in DP frameworks, providing an alternative perspective for privacy preservation.

The present study investigates the application of DP in FL systems operating with time-varying databases. In such systems, delaying updates from a client can enhance its privacy, but this may come at the cost of reduced accuracy in the trained FL model. Therefore, we build upon the research presented in [11], further exploring how the aging of data impacts both privacy and the accuracy of the trained FL model. Our objective is to highlight the potential benefit of scheduling in FL under a DP constraint. To this end, we develop a scheduling policy that governs the timing of data collection and the level of noise injection for each client. The primary aim of this scheduling design is to minimize accuracy loss difference in the trained FL model while ensuring compliance with pre-established privacy constraints.

Some prior research has explored the concept of data freshness in FL systems. For example, [12] studied a federated learning problem involving fast-changing datasets. An FL protocol was developed where uplink and downlink updates are triggered only when specific numbers of clients are available and reported, respectively. The study characterized the average age of information for the considered protocol and optimized the amounts of clients it needed to wait. In [13], Marfog et al. studied federated learning for data streams. In this scenario, data arrives sequentially during the training process, and each client can only store a portion of it due to limited memory. A modified stochastic gradient descent was proposed that assigns each sample a weight based on its observed time. However, these prior studies did not tackle the privacy concern and did not investigate the impact of scheduling.

To address the aforementioned tradeoff, in this paper, we consider a privacy-sensitive federated learning model in a time-varying system. The data collected by each client at different times may be different, following a Markov process that varies from client to client. Moreover, the server is well aware of the varying behaviors of clients’ data. The general FL model that we have considered covers the conventional version in which all procedures are assumed to be finished at the same time. See the illustration of our time-varying FL model in Fig. 1. In the literature, it is known that privacy can be provided by data aging [11] and adding artificial noise [4, 5, 6], each approach having a different impact on prediction accuracy, hinting at the benefit of scheduling.

This study marks the first attempt to examine the three-way trade-off between data freshness, privacy, and the accuracy of FL. We provide a three-client toy example to show the phenomenon. Fig. 2 demonstrates that collecting data at different scheduled time under a specific privacy guarantee for each client may affect the accuracy loss of the global model. Moreover, with the different setting of data varying of each client, the trade-off may also be different. For example, by choosing the freshest collection time of the second and third clients and varying that of Client 1, Fig. 2(a) shows that training the local model with the fresher data and adding the relative DP noise to guarantee each client’s privacy level results in less accuracy loss. Alternatively, Fig. 2(b) and Fig. 2(c) show that an optimal scheduled data collection time exists to minimize the accuracy loss under the same privacy guarantee for each client. Thus, neither the freshest data nor the stalest data provide the minimum accuracy loss of the FL global model. The details of the simulation setup are given in Section IV. First, we recognize the transfer learning nature in the considered learning task and extend a recent bound on the generalization error of transfer learning [14] to our model, thereby upper-bounding the loss difference. An optimization problem is then formulated, aiming to find the optimal policy that results in the minimum loss difference while meeting the privacy constraint. Based on our analytical results and those in [11], a procedure is developed to find suitable scheduling for clients, who then adaptively adjust the noise levels according to the privacy requirement and the ages of the data. Simulation results show that the proposed policy achieves a better accuracy-privacy trade-off than benchmark schemes that perform random scheduling and/or non-adaptive noise.

The rest of the paper is organized as follows: In Section II, we discuss preliminaries, including notational conventions, the system model, age-dependent Differential Privacy (DP), and the formulated problem. In Section III, we present our analysis of the loss difference and the proposed FL protocol. Simulation results, along with some discussion, are provided in Section IV, followed by the conclusion in Section V.

II-C Age-dependent Differential Privacy

We assume the server is honest, but there exist external adversaries who may have access to w(tagg)superscript𝑤subscript𝑡aggw^{(t_{\textnormal{agg}})} and aim to obtain sensitive information from the clients through w(tagg)superscript𝑤subscript𝑡aggw^{(t_{\textnormal{agg}})}. One approach to ensure privacy is to employ classical differential privacy (DP) mechanisms on both each client’s update wi(tc,i)superscriptsubscript𝑤𝑖subscript𝑡c𝑖w_{i}^{(t_{\textrm{c},i})} and the aggregated model w(tagg)superscript𝑤subscript𝑡aggw^{(t_{\textnormal{agg}})} [8]. In this work, we choose to implement DP mechanisms solely on the client side for simplicity and explore both classic DP and age-dependent DP mechanisms.

II-D Problem Formulation

As we mentioned in Section I, the PS should first schedule the clients when to perform data collection and upload their parameters in order to deploy the well-train model at a specific time. Moreover, we know that using different times of data can provide different privacy levels but bring penalties to the accuracy of the global model. In this paper, we first characterize the accuracy loss difference between the global model’s accuracy loss, which is governed by a set of specific scheduling times {tc,i}i∈[m]subscriptsubscript𝑡c𝑖𝑖delimited-[]𝑚\{t_{\textnormal{c},i}\}_{i\in[m]} with the corresponding age-dependent DP mechanisms, and that of the optimal well-trained model, which is the model trained by the freshest data without applying any privacy mechanism. III Main Results

Towards solving the problem stated above, in Section III-A, we first prove an upper bound on the loss difference caused by the age of information. Based on this bound, we then present the proposed scheduling algorithm in Section III-B.

III-B Proposed Federated Learning Protocol

Given the privacy requirement ϵ¯¯italic-ϵ\bar{\epsilon} and the model deployment time taggsubscript𝑡aggt_{\textnormal{agg}}, our FL protocol is as follows:

  • •

    Step 1 (Scheduling of data collection time): The PS schedules the data collection time ℐ=(tc,1,tc,2,…,tc,n)ℐsubscript𝑡c1subscript𝑡c2…subscript𝑡c𝑛\mathcal{I}=(t_{\textnormal{c},1},t_{\textnormal{c},2},...,t_{\textnormal{c},n}) and informs the client i𝑖i its scheduled time tc,isubscript𝑡c𝑖t_{\textnormal{c},i}.

  • •

    Step 2 (Local training): The client i∈[m]𝑖delimited-[]𝑚i\in[m] collects data at its scheduled time tc,isubscript𝑡c𝑖t_{\textnormal{c},i} and performs ERM to train the local model.

  • •

    Step 3 (Adaptive noise power calculation): The client i∈[m]𝑖delimited-[]𝑚i\in[m] computes its ϵc,isubscriptitalic-ϵc𝑖\epsilon_{\textnormal{c},i} based on its Δi​(tagg−tc,i)subscriptΔ𝑖subscript𝑡aggsubscript𝑡c𝑖\Delta_{i}(t_{\textnormal{agg}}-t_{\textnormal{c},i})

    ϵc,i=ln⁡(1Δi​(tagg−tc,i)​(exp⁡(ϵ¯)−1)+1),subscriptitalic-ϵ𝑐𝑖1subscriptΔ𝑖subscript𝑡aggsubscript𝑡c𝑖¯italic-ϵ11\epsilon_{c,i}=\ln\left(\frac{1}{\Delta_{i}(t_{\textnormal{agg}}-t_{\textnormal{c},i})}(\exp(\bar{\epsilon})-1)+1\right), (5)

    where (5) is obtained from (1). This ϵc,isubscriptitalic-ϵc𝑖\epsilon_{\textnormal{c},i} represents the amount of DP that the classical mechanism needs to provide to maintain the overall DP requirement ϵ¯¯italic-ϵ\bar{\epsilon}. In this paper, we adopt the Laplace mechanism, we add at client i𝑖i a Laplace noise with parameter η≡s(f)/ϵc,i𝜂superscript𝑠𝑓subscriptitalic-ϵc𝑖\eta\equiv s^{(f)}/\epsilon_{\textnormal{c},i}, which follows the distribution,

    pL​(x|η)=12​η​exp⁡(−|x|η),subscript𝑝𝐿conditional𝑥𝜂12𝜂𝑥𝜂p_{L}(x|\eta)=\frac{1}{2\eta}\exp\left(-\frac{|x|}{\eta}\right), (6)

    where si(f)superscriptsubscript𝑠𝑖𝑓s_{i}^{(f)} is the ℓ1subscriptℓ1\ell_{1}-sensitivity of the underlying learning algorithm f𝑓f (we adopt ERM in Section IV) given by

    si(f)≜max𝒟i,𝒟i′∥f(𝒟i)−f(𝒟i′)∥1.s_{i}^{(f)}\triangleq\max_{\mathcal{D}_{i},\mathcal{D}_{i}^{\prime}}\lVert f(\mathcal{D}_{i})-f(\mathcal{D}_{i}^{\prime})\rVert_{1}. (7)

With the above analysis, we can now use the upper bound in (4) as a surrogate to solve the optimization problem in (3a). Specifically, for each scheduling policy ℐ=(tc,1,tc,2,…,tc,n)ℐsubscript𝑡c1subscript𝑡c2…subscript𝑡c𝑛\mathcal{I}=(t_{\textnormal{c},1},t_{\textnormal{c},2},...,t_{\textnormal{c},n}), we use (4) to calculate an upper bound on the loss difference. We repeat this for every policy ℐℐ\mathcal{I} and find ℐ∗superscriptℐ\mathcal{I}^{*} that minimizes the upper bound. It is obvious that as the number of clients and how old the data we can tolerate increases, the computational complexity becomes unacceptable. Hence, it is crucial to design low-complexity algorithms that can efficiently find optimal scheduling, which is left for future work.

IV Discussion and Simulation

In this section, we present simulation results to validate our analysis and showcase the efficacy of the proposed FL protocol. We first introduce the simulation setting in Section IV-A and then discuss our results in Section IV-B.

IV-A Setting

We consider the similar electricity consumption forecast experiment described in [11]. In this scenario, a PS aims to train a global model to estimate the mean electricity consumption of households in London. Under a privacy-sensitive system, we assume three clients exist in the system. i.e., m=3𝑚3m=3. Unlike [11], we assume each client’s electricity consumption at scheduled time tc,isubscript𝑡c𝑖t_{\textnormal{c},i} follows πisubscript𝜋𝑖\pi_{i} and the transition probability matrix from tc,i+j−1subscript𝑡c𝑖𝑗1t_{\textnormal{c},i}+j-1 to tc,i+jsubscript𝑡c𝑖𝑗t_{\textnormal{c},i}+j is 𝖯isubscript𝖯𝑖\mathsf{P}_{i} for every j∈ℕ𝑗ℕj\in\mathbb{N}, both may vary from client to client. Specifically, the initial probability distributions for the three clients are set to be π1=[0.8,0.2,0,0]Tsubscript𝜋1superscript0.80.200𝑇\pi_{1}=[0.8,0.2,0,0]^{T}, π2=[0,0.1,0.5,0.4]Tsubscript𝜋2superscript00.10.50.4𝑇\pi_{2}=[0,0.1,0.5,0.4]^{T} and π3=[0.2,0.3,0.5,0]Tsubscript𝜋3superscript0.20.30.50𝑇\pi_{3}=[0.2,0.3,0.5,0]^{T}, respectively.

In our system, each client samples 100 data at time tc,isubscript𝑡c𝑖t_{\textnormal{c},i} individually and performs local training using the ERM algorithm and the loss function as the mean square error to achieve optimal local weights. Subsequently, it uploads these weights to the PS. We assume that only one client can upload the local weights to the PS at a time. After receiving all clients’ weights, the PS aggregates them and obtains the global weights at time taggsubscript𝑡aggt_{\text{agg}}.

To simplify the problem, we quantize the electricity consumption per half hour into four possible values: 20, 50, 100, and 200 (in Wh). Moreover, we assume that the variation in electricity consumption can be formulated as a four-state birth-and-death Markov chain, where the transition probability matrix is expressed as:

IV-B Results

We present the simulation results. We consider the following schemes: 1) Random scheduling ++ constant noise: We randomly select scheduled times tc,isubscript𝑡c𝑖t_{\textnormal{c},i} and a constant noise parameter is used for every client regardless of tc,isubscript𝑡c𝑖t_{\textnormal{c},i}. 2) Random scheduling ++ adaptive noise: We randomly select scheduled times tc,isubscript𝑡c𝑖t_{\textnormal{c},i} and each client adds a noise according to (5). 3) Proposed scheduling ++ constant noise: Fix a constant noise level, find the scheduling that achieves the minimum loss difference according to Theorem 1, and use this policy to determine its achievable ϵ¯¯italic-ϵ\bar{\epsilon}. 4) Proposed scheduling ++ adaptive noise: For each scheduling, we adaptively add noise so that ϵ¯¯italic-ϵ\bar{\epsilon} is satisfied. We then find the scheduling that results in minimum loss difference according to Theorem 1. 5) Optimal scheduling ++ constant noise: Similar to 3) but use simulation instead of Theorem 1. 6) Optimal scheduling ++ adaptive noise: Similar to 4) but use simulation instead of Theorem 1.

One can expect that 1) and 2) would not perform well as they do not take scheduling into their design. Moreover, 3) would not perform well even though scheduling is taken into account, because each client needs to add constant noise to meet the privacy requirement for the worst client, compromising the accuracy. On the other hand, the proposed approach in 4) will perform the best, as it jointly considers scheduling and adaptive noise. Furthermore, 5) and 6) are simulated to showcase the effectiveness of Theorem 1.

In the simulation results depicted in Fig. 3(a), as anticipated, it is evident that approaches 1) and 2) exhibit subpar performance due to the absence of scheduling considerations in their design. Likewise, approach 3) does not excel even with scheduling incorporated, as each client introduces a constant noise to meet the privacy requirement for the worst client, consequently compromising accuracy. In contrast, the proposed approach in 4) outperforms all others. By simultaneously considering scheduling and adaptive noise, it achieves the lowest loss difference. This underscores the effectiveness of our comprehensive approach in striking a balance between privacy and accuracy. Moreover, comparing the simulation results of 3) with 5) and those of 4) with 6) reveals that Theorem 1 accurately captures the trade-off and guides us towards proper scheduling designs. This validation highlights the robustness and applicability of the theoretical framework proposed in the paper. The simulation results in Fig. 3(b) show the noise power that we have to add in each scheme. Here, ϵc≜1m​∑i=1mϵc,i≜subscriptitalic-ϵc1𝑚superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑚subscriptitalic-ϵc𝑖\epsilon_{\textnormal{c}}\triangleq\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}\epsilon_{\textnormal{c},i}. The noise power of the schemes that add a constant noise to meet the privacy requirement is always larger than adaptive noise schemes, whether the scheduling is taken into consideration or not.

V Conclusion

This paper investigated the intricate relationship between data aging, DP, and accuracy within FL systems, particularly in the context of time-varying databases. We introduced an age-dependent upper bound on the FL loss difference, providing a theoretical foundation for our research. Leveraging this bound, we devised a scheduling algorithm to minimize the loss difference while adhering to age-dependent DP constraints. Our findings indicate that the proposed FL system surpasses FL systems that overlook aging into the design by concurrently optimizing both the data collection timing and the noise injection level. An interesting and important future work is to design low-complexity age-aware scheduling policies.
